      "text": ":<i>Measuring an AI by the output rather than how the processing is performed is okay. All one needs to do is define the correct sort of tests. The test I defined for 'proof of understanding' is the ability to take a lot of input data, (black-box process it), then produce and communicate a summary. A summary must have the following characteristics: <b>(a)</b> it is considerably smaller than the original data set, <b>(b)</b> it is at a higher abstraction than the original data-set, <b>(c)</b> it hits the most important features necessary to reproduce a facsimile of the data-set with a certain degree of fidelity.</i> ",
      "id": "d238637477e828b09e134607f1bd20a5"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "text": ":<i>These are part and parcel to the common definition of 'summary'. One should note that 'features' are utilized opposite of abstractions... e.g. 'red' applied to 'apple' is a feature, whereas 'red' applied to a 'clump of pixels' is an abstraction. The production of <b>a summary proves understanding to any intelligence that has both the original data-set and agrees that the reproduced facsimile is within the specified degree of fidelity</b> (the summary may be translated, if necessary). It often is useful to prove understanding to oneself as a form of auditing one's knowledge. 'Higher abstraction' is defined in such a way that prevents many forms of lossless and lossy data-compression (including simple transformations of representation as per JPEG or LZW. Transformations and translations, in general, cannot constitute proof of understanding). Essentially, production of a 'summary' requires semantic compression.</i>",
      "id": "263748ed343a7978bcc255722559d737"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "text": ":<i>I've found nobody so far who does not agree that 'understanding' (in its common, English understanding) is not sufficiently proven by production of this summary. I've seen initial disagreements as to whether component is necessary, or to whether this is the only possible proof of understanding... but, in general, thought-experiments have revealed that alternative proofs are largely equivalent to this one, and removing requirements results in something less than understanding (... as it is commonly understood...). Anyhow, this provides you the opportunity to <b>measure AI by the output</b>. You can now measure understanding. And by that, I mean 'understanding' sufficient to qualify for the English use of the term.</i>",
      "id": "57dd7480e3e4dc2216c6bbcfa07bbf45"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "text": " Many humans are not able to create good or usable summaries, especially the poorly educated. I think that is too strict a test. If you wish to define that as *your* target AI goal, I have no problem with that as your working frame of reference; but, it is not a definition that I would use. I think it creates too big of a risk of a \"summary savant\". Or, at least I wouldn't put all my eggs in that one criteria. A <b>multi-test score-card</b> approach may be more effective. Summarizing would be one of many tests. If they flunk summaries but pass other tests, then perhaps they could be forgiven for such a flaw. This is generally how we evaluate human abilities also. Somebody who may be a great auto-mechanic may be crappy at descriptive summaries, for example. But they are still a valuable member of society even if the boss or coworkers have to help him/her sometimes when he talks to a customer. Some geeks are like this: unable to turn shop-talk into something non-techies can relate to. -- top",
      "id": "524aba6d09d7b563368a49b489e69bdd"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "text": " <i>Many humans lack understanding of the topics about which they are </i>tested<i> by request for provision of a summary. This is especially true of the poorly educated. However, their ability to </i>prove<i> understanding is often hampered by their inability to communicate. Thus inability to prove understanding doesn't necessarily mean understanding doesn't exist (see my original discussion of how 'understanding' differs from 'proof of understanding', below). Every proof to some other intelligence requires communication, so there is no getting around that. However, there are alternative, often weaker proofs of understanding... e.g. (from stronger to weaker) via asking of open-ended trick questions (tests recognition and rejection, and synthesis... same as full summary), via asking of open-ended leading questions (tests recognition and synthesis), via asking of multiple-choice questions (tests recognition only), via multiple-choice questions with some 'none of the above' answers (tests recognition and rejection), request for examples (tests synthesis only). The open-ended trick questions test all the same things as a full summary... if you can provide a complete summary or definition, you can answer those questions, and vice versa. However, the others you might reasonably 'lesser forms' of understanding. I'd call them 'partial' understandings, seeing as none of them individually meet the proof requirements I set forward when I was initially formalizing my understanding of <b>understanding</b>.</i>",
      "id": "1e61971b59be65afc2b689cd90f59b07"
    },
